<div class='main'>

			<div class='running-text'>
			<p><b>(WORK)SHOPS</b></p>
			<p><i>Flexible Marketplace</i></p>
			<p><b>Date</b> 2012<br/>
			<b>Location</b> 128 North Main Street Providence, RI<br/>
			<b>Size</b> 9,000 sq. ft.</p>
				
			<p>The end of shopping as a physically-located experience, and the end of craft in favor of mass-production have led to the deterioration of the shop as a place for the shaping of individual and communal identity.  However, we must acknowledge that for efficiency and economics, mass-production has a place in retail design. Through the insertion of several small shops and workshops in a vacant space along Providence's Main Street, this project proposes that a compromise between traditional craft and contemporary mass-production methods can deliver an idiosyncratic experience that preserves the localness of a city and its community, while providing flexibility for future growth.</p>
			</div>
